policy-makers in Paris – and quite as often been denounced as ‘the longest scandal of the republic’ by French academics and African intellectuals. Between the last years of French colonialism and France’s sustained interventions in former African colonies such as Chad or Côte d’Ivoire during the 2000s, the legacy of French colonialism has shaped the historical trajectory of more than a dozen countries and societies in Africa. The complexities of this story are now, for the first time, addressed in a comprehensive series of essays, based on new research by a group of specialists in French colonial history. The book addresses the needs of both academic specialists and those of students of history and neighbouring disciplines looking for structural analysis of key themes in France’s and Africa’s shared history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican leaders.  aAnglo-French relations.  aFranco-African relations.  aFrench colonial empire.  aGaston Defferre.  aGuinea-Conakry.  aMali.  aMauritanian independence.  aSouthern Rhodesia.  aconflicted memories.  aeducational cooperation.  aloi-cadre.  amilitary transitions.  apost-colonial relations.1 aBat, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChafer, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChafer, Tony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCharbonneau, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvrard, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinio, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeitz, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoly, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https